{"key":"processedPost-9041530","value":{"id":9041530,"first":9038523,"last":9047179,"when":1223397235,"utime":"10/07/08 07:33 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Ground Egg shells.&nbsp; Fuck anything else.&nbsp; Egg shells are free.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />They also take well over a year to break down and become available, so are totally worthless for mycology.&nbsp; In fact, I recently spread out some four year old compost, and the egg shells were still intact, so they're of minimal use for gardens as well.<br /><br />You don't need calcium carb in your substrates, and it's of minimal benefit in casing layers.&nbsp; I'd suggest using gypsum at up to 10% by volume in both, and add some hydrated lime to your casing layers to raise the pH to a level that makes it inhospitable to mold spore germination.&nbsp; Search posts using my name and hydrated lime for all the info you'll need on the subject.<br />RR","title":"Re: question about hermit crab sand","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}